           <h2 class="section-title">Our Story</h2>
           <div class="about-content">
               <div class="about-text">
                   <h3>How It All Began (2019-2021)</h3>
                   <p>Returning to Kakuma in June 2021, after completing my high school education, was a plunge into the unexpected. Having graduated in 2019 with high hopes for college, the sharp reality hit hard ‚Äî the odds were stacked against me. The Kenyan government's policies offered limited opportunities for "foreign students" like myself.</p>
                   
                   <p>Desperate for a way forward, I grasped onto the chance to teach within the refugee camp. Simultaneously, I became part of the <strong>Elimisha Kakuma program</strong>, headed by three former refugees who pursued education in the United States. At the camp, I shared a bed with a fellow teacher, while fourteen other young boys in our compound looked to me for guidance and education.</p>
                   
                   <p>Each morning, I would go to the Elimisha Center, assuming the role of both a tech support member and a student. Weekends were dedicated to volunteering in schools and hospitals, peeling back layers of this community's reality. <strong>I discovered a harsh truth: many children in the camp faced the raw challenges of refugee life alone.</strong></p>
                   
                   <h3>Building a Family (2021-2023)</h3>
                   <p>In Kakuma, numerous young souls arrive unaccompanied, thrown into a community where living alone is not an option. I met <strong>three boys</strong> who had no family, no shelter, and no support. Their names stayed with me, and their need became my responsibility.</p>
                   
                   <p>With community fundraising, I built a small shelter for them. We added solar panels for light and safety, provided daily meals, and enrolled them in school. Word spread. More children came ‚Äî children who had lost everything but hope. <strong>At our peak, we were supporting 18 children.</strong> We taught them life skills, discipline, and community values. It wasn't perfect, but it was a home.</p>
                   
                   <h3>The Crisis of 2025</h3>
                   <p>In early 2025, <strong>USAID food rations were drastically cut.</strong> The boys, classified as "extremely vulnerable," began losing their food support. Violence increased in the camp. <strong>Seven of our boys were forced to leave for their safety or survival.</strong></p>
                   
                   <p>Today, we support <strong>11 boys and 1 girl</strong> who remain, plus <strong>3 children from my sister's family</strong> who needed urgent care ‚Äî a total of <strong>14 children</strong>. They need $400 per month for food, school supplies, and basic survival.</p>
                   
                   <h3>Who Are "Makol's Boys"?</h3>
                   <p>In Kakuma, people call them <strong>Makol's Boys</strong> ‚Äî not as an official name, but as a community identity. It's a nickname that grew naturally from the bond we share. It reflects connection and responsibility. As my tutor Anika Brennan would always say: <em>"Whatever you learn, teach two other people."</em></p>
                   
                   <p><strong>My vision is to witness these children thrive despite the adversities that swarm around them.</strong> I refuse to accept a reality where their youth becomes a liability. My aim is to foster an environment where they flourish, triumphing over circumstances that unfairly put the odds against them.</p>
                   
